    "IND_FRD": {
      "name": "Fractal Dimension",
      "definition": "IND_FRD is a quantitative measure of morphological complexity and roughness, derived from fractal geometry. In visual landscape analysis, it assesses the texture and edge complexity of skylines or vegetation patterns, typically using the box-counting method. A higher fractal dimension suggests a more complex, information-rich visual environment, often resembling natural forms. This indicator is widely used in environmental psychology to predict preference, as humans tend to prefer mid-to-high fractal complexity which mimics the structural order found in nature.",
      "category": "CAT_CFG",
      "formula": "Db = lim (r->0) [log N(r) / log (1/r)]",
